President Joe Biden has announced his intent to nominate Dennis B. Hankins as the Ambassador Extraordinary and Plenipotentiary to the Republic of Haiti. Hankins is a career member of the Senior Foreign Service and currently serves as the Foreign Policy Advisor to the National Guard Bureau at the Pentagon. He has previously served as Ambassador to the Republic of Mali and to the Republic of Guinea, as well as in various diplomatic roles in countries such as Sudan, Mauritania, Mozambique, and Saudi Arabia. Hankins has also served in Haiti as the Nonimmigrant Visa Chief and the Refugee Coordinator. He holds a B.S.F.S. from Georgetown University and an M.S. from the National War College.

Additionally, James C. O'Brien has been nominated for the position of Assistant Secretary of State for European and Eurasian Affairs. O'Brien currently serves as Head of the Office of Sanctions Coordination at the U.S. Department of State. He has previously worked as a special Presidential envoy, Senior Advisor to former Secretary Madeleine Albright, Principal Deputy Director of Policy Planning, and Presidential Envoy for the Balkans. O'Brien played a significant role in peace negotiations in Europe, post-Soviet transitions in Russia and Ukraine, and efforts to investigate and prosecute war crimes. He was also the first Presidential Envoy for Hostage Affairs, working towards the safe return of American citizens. O'Brien holds a J.D. from Yale Law School, an M.A. from the University of Pittsburgh, and a B.A. from Macalester College.